# 4. S3 configurations file format

Date: 2026-01-14

## Status

Proposed

## Context and Problem Statement

In order to allow the Lambda version of the Refiner to read configurations without direct database access, we need to be able to write a serialized version of that configuration to an S3 bucket that the Lambda will be able to access, parse, and use for refinement.

The goal of this document is to outline what that serialized file format should look like and explain why the selected properties are needed.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> This document only describes the file format itself. Please see [S3 file structure for activations](0003_2026-01-06_activation-s3-file-structure.md) to understand how these files will be stored and accessed.

## Decision Outcome

The activation file will be written in JSON format and will have the following properties:

- `codes`: an array of condition codes to use for eICR filtering
- `sections`: an array of objects containing information related to eICR section filtering
- `included_condition_rsg_codes`: an array of child RSG codes for all conditions associated with the configuration, required for RR filtering

This file will always be named `active.json`

Here is a minimal example of what the `active.json` file will look like:

```json
{
    "codes": ["string"],
    "sections": [
        {
            "code": "string",
            "name": "string",
            "action": "string"
        }
    ],
    "included_condition_rsg_codes": ["string"]
}
```
